From: jaewun <jaewun@users.noreply.github.com>
Subject: [PATCH] scsi: ufs: qcom: keep M-PHY powered across hibern8 parking on no_phy_retention

The SM8550 qcom host is flagged no_phy_retention: its M-PHY loses ALL
calibrated SerDes/lane/PCS state on any phy_power_off (qmp_ufs_power_off ->
regulator_bulk_disable of vdda-phy/vdda-pll). The only code that recalibrates
is ufs_qcom_power_up_sequence() -> phy_calibrate(), reached only through a full
link-startup (reset_and_restore).

ufs_qcom_setup_clocks(on=false) calls phy_power_off() UNCONDITIONALLY, on every
SW clk-gate and every rpm_lvl=3 runtime-PM suspend that merely parks the link in
HIBERN8. The matching ungate/runtime-resume then issues a bare UIC hibern8-EXIT
(DME_HIBERNATE_EXIT), which assumes a retained, calibrated PHY -- so on the now
decalibrated PHY it times out: "pwr ctrl cmd 0x18 ... completion timeout" ->
"hibern8 exit failed ret=-110" -> ufshcd_set_link_broken -> dead UFS link. This
is the dominant, load-independent face of the wedge (it fires on idle micro-gap
clk-gating). The clk-scaling gear-change exit hits the same trap because the PHY
was already decalibrated by a prior gate/runtime cycle.

Fix: on no_phy_retention hosts, when the link is merely parked in HIBERN8, keep
the PHY powered -- skip phy_power_off() on the way down and the matching
phy_power_on() on the way up. phy_power_off/on are refcounted (drivers/phy:
ops fire only on the 1<->0 power_count transition), and uic_link_state reads
HIBERN8 at BOTH the gate-descent setup_clocks(false) (after set_link_hibern8)
and the ungate-ascent setup_clocks(true) (before hibern8-exit), so skipping both
is refcount-exact (power_count stays pinned at 1). The bare hibern8-EXIT then
always relocks on a calibrated PHY. True LINK_OFF (system suspend, spm_lvl=5)
is unchanged: it still powers the PHY off and recalibrates via reset_and_restore
on resume. Strictly gated on no_phy_retention, so MCQ and all other hosts are
byte-for-byte unchanged.

---
--- a/drivers/ufs/host/ufs-qcom.c
+++ b/drivers/ufs/host/ufs-qcom.c
@@ -1253,7 +1253,9 @@
 				 enum ufs_notify_change_status status)
 {
 	struct ufs_qcom_host *host = ufshcd_get_variant(hba);
+	const struct ufs_qcom_drvdata *drvdata;
 	struct phy *phy;
+	bool keep_phy;
 	int err;
 
 	/*
@@ -1264,7 +1266,23 @@
 	if (!host)
 		return 0;
 
+	drvdata = of_device_get_match_data(hba->dev);
 	phy = host->generic_phy;
+
+	/*
+	 * no_phy_retention hosts (e.g. SM8550) lose ALL calibrated M-PHY state
+	 * on any phy_power_off (qmp_ufs_power_off -> regulator_bulk_disable of
+	 * vdda-phy/vdda-pll); the only recalibration is a full link-startup
+	 * (reset_and_restore). A bare UIC hibern8-EXIT assumes retained PHY
+	 * state and times out -110 on a decalibrated PHY. So when the link is
+	 * merely parked in HIBERN8 (SW clk-gating and rpm_lvl=3 runtime PM),
+	 * keep the PHY powered: skip phy_power_off here and the matching
+	 * phy_power_on below. power_count stays pinned at 1 so the skip is
+	 * refcount-exact. True LINK_OFF (system suspend) still powers the PHY
+	 * off and recalibrates via reset_and_restore on resume.
+	 */
+	keep_phy = drvdata && drvdata->no_phy_retention &&
+		   ufs_qcom_is_link_hibern8(hba);
 
 	switch (status) {
 	case PRE_CHANGE:
@@ -1283,19 +1301,23 @@
 				ufs_qcom_dev_ref_clk_ctrl(host, false);
 			}
 
-			err = phy_power_off(phy);
-			if (err) {
-				dev_err(hba->dev, "phy power off failed, ret=%d\n", err);
-				return err;
+			if (!keep_phy) {
+				err = phy_power_off(phy);
+				if (err) {
+					dev_err(hba->dev, "phy power off failed, ret=%d\n", err);
+					return err;
+				}
 			}
 		}
 		break;
 	case POST_CHANGE:
 		if (on) {
-			err = phy_power_on(phy);
-			if (err) {
-				dev_err(hba->dev, "phy power on failed, ret = %d\n", err);
-				return err;
+			if (!keep_phy) {
+				err = phy_power_on(phy);
+				if (err) {
+					dev_err(hba->dev, "phy power on failed, ret = %d\n", err);
+					return err;
+				}
 			}
 
 			/* enable the device ref clock for HS mode*/
